Problem Statement¶

Context¶

AllLife Bank is a US bank that has a growing customer base. The majority of these customers are liability customers (depositors) with varying sizes of deposits. The number of customers who are also borrowers (asset customers) is quite small, and the bank is interested in expanding this base rapidly to bring in more loan business and in the process, earn more through the interest on loans. In particular, the management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors).

A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio.

You as a Data scientist at AllLife bank have to build a model that will help the marketing department to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability of purchasing the loan.

Objective¶

To predict whether a liability customer will buy personal loans, to understand which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases, and identify which segment of customers to target more.

Data Dictionary¶

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customers age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family: the Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate;3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousand dollars)
  • Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Securities_Account: Does the customer have securities account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Online: Do customers use internet banking facilities? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All life Bank)? (0: No, 1: Yes)

def create_boxplot(data, numeric_features, hue=None):
    columns = 2
    rows = int(np.ceil(len(numeric_features) / columns))

    fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, columns, figsize=(14, 5 * rows))
    axes = axes.flatten()  # Make it easier to index
    legend_labels = None

    for i, feature in enumerate(numeric_features):
        ax = axes[i]
        plot = sns.boxplot(data=data, x=feature, hue=hue, ax=ax)
        ax.set_title(f"Boxplot for {feature}")

        # Store legend info from first plot only
        if i == 0 and hue:
            handles, labels = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()
            legend_labels = (handles, labels)

        # Remove legend from all but the first subplot
        if hue:
            ax.legend_.remove()

    # Hide any unused subplots
    for j in range(i + 1, len(axes)):
        fig.delaxes(axes[j])

    # Add the legend at the top center
    if legend_labels:
        fig.legend(*legend_labels, loc='upper center', ncol=len(legend_labels[1]), fontsize='medium')

    plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0, 1, 0.95])  # leave space at top for legend
    plt.show()

Observations¶

For the numerical features:

  • Customers have an median age of 45 years, with age following a normal distribution
  • Customers also possess a median work experience of 20 years, with work experience following a normal distribution
  • Customers have an median income of 64k. Income shows a positive skewness, with some customers having a higher than usual income
  • Average spend on credit cards made by customers is around 1.5K per month, with many customers having also spent higher than usual amounts per month, ranging upto 10K per month
  • On average, amongst customers who have taken a mortgage, average mortgage amount is around ~183K. However, mortgage is positively skewed, with many customers having much higher mortgage amounts (max:635K)

For the categorical features:

  • Almost 70% of customers have 2 or more members (including themselves) in their family
  • Around 10% of customers have a securities account
  • Only 6% of the customers have a certificate of deposit
  • 60% of customers have & use online banking facilities
  • 30% of the customers own a credit card
  • Dependent Variable: Around 10% (480) customers had previously accepted a personal loan

def create_barplot(data, numeric_features, hue=None):
    columns = 2
    rows = int(np.ceil(len(numeric_features) / columns))

    fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, columns, figsize=(14, 5 * rows))
    axes = axes.flatten()  # Make it easier to index
    legend_labels = None

    for i, feature in enumerate(numeric_features):
        ax = axes[i]
        plot = sns.barplot(data=data, y=feature, hue=hue, ax=ax)
        ax.set_title(f"Avg {feature} By Acceptance Of Personal Loan")

    # Hide any unused subplots
    for j in range(i + 1, len(axes)):
        fig.delaxes(axes[j])

    plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0, 1, 0.95])  # leave space at top for legend
    plt.show()

def create_histplot(data, numeric_features, hue=None):
    if not numeric_features:
        print(" No numeric features provided. Skipping histplot generation.")
        return

    columns = 2
    rows = int(np.ceil(len(numeric_features) / columns))

    fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, columns, figsize=(14, 5 * rows))
    axes = axes.flatten()
    legend_labels = None

    for i, feature in enumerate(numeric_features):
        ax = axes[i]
        plot = sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, hue=hue, ax=ax, kde=True)
        ax.set_title(f"Histogram for {feature}")

        # Store legend info from first plot only
        if i == 0 and hue:
            handles, labels = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()
            legend_labels = (handles, labels)

        # Remove legend from other plots safely
        if hue and ax.get_legend() is not None:
            ax.get_legend().remove()

    # Hide any unused subplots
    for j in range(i + 1, len(axes)):
        fig.delaxes(axes[j])

    # Add a shared legend
    if legend_labels and len(legend_labels[0]) > 0:
        fig.legend(*legend_labels, loc='upper center', ncol=len(legend_labels[1]), fontsize='medium')


    plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0, 1, 0.95])
    plt.show()

def create_countplots(data, categorical_features, hue=None):
    """
    Creates countplots for each categorical feature, optionally broken down by hue.

    Parameters:
    - data: pandas DataFrame
    - categorical_features: list of column names (categorical variables)
    - hue: column name for hue-based breakdown (optional)
    """
    columns = 2
    rows = int(np.ceil(len(categorical_features) / columns))

    fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, columns, figsize=(14, 5 * rows))
    axes = axes.flatten()
    legend_labels = None

    for i, feature in enumerate(categorical_features):
        ax = axes[i]
        sns.countplot(data=data, x=feature, hue=hue, ax=ax,stat = 'percent')
        ax.set_title(f"% Total Of {feature}")
        ax.tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)

        # Save legend from first plot
        if i == 0 and hue:
            handles, labels = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()
            legend_labels = (handles, labels)

        # Remove legend from all but first
        if hue and ax.get_legend() is not None and i != 0:
            ax.get_legend().remove()

    # Hide unused axes
    for j in range(i + 1, len(axes)):
        fig.delaxes(axes[j])

    # Add shared legend
    if hue and legend_labels:
        fig.legend(*legend_labels, loc='upper center', ncol=len(legend_labels[1]), fontsize='medium')

    plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0, 1, 0.95])
    plt.show()

Key Observations¶

We'll look into the relationship between the dependent feature Personal_Loan and other independent features to understand the difference in trends or patterns amongst custoemrs who accepted a Personal loan and those who didn't

  • We don't see any difference in age and experience amongst customers who did and who didn't accept personal loan

  • Income: Customers who accepted a Personal Loan had on average a higher annual income i.e ~142k vs customer didn't i.e ~60K. This implies customers with higher income have a better financial capacity to pay back a loan and might be more attractive prospects for the bank to target.

  • CCAvg: Customers who accepted a Personal Loan had an average credit card spend tendency i.e 3.8K per month vs those who didn't (1.4K). This could imply that customers who are already leveraging credit actively are more likely to engage with additional lending products like personal loans.

  • Mortgage: Amongst customers who have taken out a mortgage, customers who accepted a personal loan had an larger amount of mortgage i.e 288K vs customer who didn't accept a loan i.e 170K. This could imply that customers with higher mortgage amounts might find it favourable to accept a personal loan to pay off a mortgage or fend off other expenses

  • Family Members: Amongst customers who accepted Personal Loan, 55% of customers have 3 or 4 members vs those who didn't (45%). This could imply customers with more family members might be prospective targets for promoting personal loans to, given they have multiple family-related expenses like education, healthcare, or housing.

  • CD Account: Amongst customers who accepted Personal Loan, 30% had a certificate of deposit. Proportion of customers who didn't accept a personal loan and with a certificate of deposit is lesser than 10%. As the bank looks to turn customers who are currently depositors into borrowers with a personal loans, certificate of deposit holders will make good prospects.

  • Education: It is observed that % of loan acceptees are higher amongst with customers with higher educational credentials (i.e graduation & professional/advanced). Higher educational attainment may correlate with greater financial literacy, income potential, or willingness to take loans for lifestyle upgrades or professional development making them attractive segments to target.

import itertools

def create_scatter_matrix(data, numeric_features, hue=None, max_plots=20):
    """
    Creates scatterplots for all pairwise combinations of numeric features,
    optionally colored by a categorical `hue`.

    Parameters:
    - data: pandas DataFrame
    - numeric_features: list of column names that are numeric
    - hue: column name for category breakdown (optional)
    - max_plots: maximum number of plots to show (to avoid too many subplots)
    """
    if len(numeric_features) < 2:
        print(" At least two numeric features are required for scatterplots.")
        return

    # Get all pairwise combinations
    feature_pairs = list(itertools.combinations(numeric_features, 2))

    # Limit number of plots (optional)
    feature_pairs = feature_pairs[:max_plots]

    cols = 2
    rows = int(np.ceil(len(feature_pairs) / cols))
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, cols, figsize=(7 * cols, 5 * rows))
    axes = axes.flatten()

    for i, (x_feat, y_feat) in enumerate(feature_pairs):
        ax = axes[i]
        sns.scatterplot(data=data, x=x_feat, y=y_feat, hue=hue, ax=ax, alpha=0.7)
        ax.set_title(f"{y_feat} vs {x_feat}")

        # Clean up overlapping legends
        if hue and ax.get_legend() is not None:
            if i != 0:
                ax.get_legend().remove()

    # Hide extra axes if any
    for j in range(i + 1, len(axes)):
        fig.delaxes(axes[j])

    # Shared legend at the top
    if hue:
        handles, labels = axes[0].get_legend_handles_labels()
        if handles and labels:
            fig.legend(handles, labels, loc='upper center', ncol=len(labels), fontsize='medium')

    plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0, 1, 0.95])
    plt.show()

def create_multivariate_faceted_scatterplots(data, numeric_features, hue, level, columns=2, max_combinations=None):
    """
    Creates scatterplots for each pairwise combination of numeric features,
    faceted by levels of a categorical variable and colored by hue.

    Parameters:
    - data: pandas DataFrame
    - numeric_features: list of numeric column names
    - hue: column name to color points
    - level: column name to facet subplots
    - columns: number of columns per row of subplots
    - max_combinations: optionally limit number of feature pairs
    """
    feature_combinations = list(itertools.combinations(numeric_features, 2))
    if max_combinations:
        feature_combinations = feature_combinations[:max_combinations]

    unique_levels = data[level].dropna().unique()
    n_levels = len(unique_levels)

    for x, y in feature_combinations:
        rows = int(np.ceil(n_levels / columns))
        fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, columns, figsize=(6.5 * columns, 5 * rows))
        axes = axes.flatten()

        for i, lvl in enumerate(unique_levels):
            ax = axes[i]
            subset = data[data[level] == lvl]

            sns.scatterplot(data=subset, x=x, y=y, hue=hue, ax=ax, alpha=0.7)
            ax.set_title(f"{x} vs {y} | {level} = {lvl}")

            if i != 0 and ax.get_legend():
                ax.get_legend().remove()

        # Remove extra empty subplots
        for j in range(i + 1, len(axes)):
            fig.delaxes(axes[j])

        # Add shared legend
        handles, labels = axes[0].get_legend_handles_labels()
        if handles and labels:
            fig.legend(handles, labels, loc='upper center', ncol=len(labels), fontsize='medium',bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1.05))

        # Add border around the full figure
        fig.subplots_adjust(top=0.90)
        fig.suptitle(f"Feature Pair: {x} vs {y}", fontsize=16, fontweight='bold', color='darkgreen')
        fig.patch.set_edgecolor('black')
        fig.patch.set_linewidth(3)

        plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0, 1, 0.93])
        plt.show()

Key Observations¶

  • Customers who accepted a personal loan tend to exhibit both high annual income and higher average monthly credit card spend.This combination suggests strong purchasing power and financial activity, making them ideal targets for personalized loan offers with premium benefits.

  • Also, Customers who have accepted a personal loan tend to have high income but also higher mortgage amounts. These customers may be more open to loan consolidation, refinancing options, or secondary personal loans to manage large existing financial commitments.

  • Most of the previous loan acceptors had more than 2 family members AND have higher Annual Income, Credit Spend or Mortgage. This group may have more diverse financial needs (education, healthcare, housing), making them more responsive to campaigns emphasizing family support and financial flexibility.

  • Customers with graduate or more advanced educational qualifications along with high annual income, mortgage and monthly credit spend have higher loan acceptance rates. These individuals may be more financially savvy and responsive to professionally packaged loan products positioned as tools for lifestyle or career advancement.

  • Certificate of Deposit holders with high income, CC Avg spend and/or mortgage also have a high proportion of personal loan acceptors. This highlights an opportunity for cross-selling personal loans to CD holders as they may already trust the bank for long-term deposits.

def evaluate_classification_model(name, model, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, cv=5):
    """
    Evaluates a classification model on cross-validation and test set.
    Returns results as a dictionary (ready to be appended to a DataFrame).

    Parameters:
        name (str): Name of the model
        model (sklearn estimator): The model to train and evaluate
        X_train, y_train: Training data
        X_test, y_test: Test data
        cv (int): Number of CV folds

    Returns:
        dict: Model name + CV and test scores for multiple metrics
    """
    # Cross-validation setup
    skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=cv, shuffle=True, random_state=42)
    cv_preds = cross_val_predict(model, X_train, y_train, cv=skf, method='predict')
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    test_preds = model.predict(X_test)

    # CV metrics
    cv_acc = accuracy_score(y_train, cv_preds)
    cv_prec = precision_score(y_train, cv_preds, zero_division=0)
    cv_rec = recall_score(y_train, cv_preds, zero_division=0)
    cv_f1 = f1_score(y_train, cv_preds, zero_division=0)

    # Test metrics
    test_acc = accuracy_score(y_test, test_preds)
    test_prec = precision_score(y_test, test_preds, zero_division=0)
    test_rec = recall_score(y_test, test_preds, zero_division=0)
    test_f1 = f1_score(y_test, test_preds, zero_division=0)

    return {
        'Model': name,
        'CV_Accuracy': round(cv_acc, 4),
        'CV_Precision': round(cv_prec, 4),
        'CV_Recall': round(cv_rec, 4),
        'CV_F1': round(cv_f1, 4),
        'Test_Accuracy': round(test_acc, 4),
        'Test_Precision': round(test_prec, 4),
        'Test_Recall': round(test_rec, 4),
        'Test_F1': round(test_f1, 4),
    }

def plot_confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, labels=None, title="Confusion Matrix", cmap="Blues"):
    """
    Plots a confusion matrix with labeled axes.

    Parameters:
        y_true (array-like): Actual labels
        y_pred (array-like): Predicted labels
        labels (list): Optional list of label names (e.g., ['No', 'Yes'])
        title (str): Title of the plot
        cmap (str): Color map for heatmap
    """
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 5))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap=cmap, xticklabels=labels, yticklabels=labels)
    plt.title(title, fontsize=14, pad=10)
    plt.xlabel("Predicted", fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel("Actual", fontsize=12)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def print_classification_report(y_true, y_pred, target_names=None):
    """
    Prints a classification report with precision, recall, f1-score, and support.

    Parameters:
        y_true (array-like): True labels
        y_pred (array-like): Predicted labels
        target_names (list): Optional class label names (e.g., ['Not Campaign', 'Campaign'])
    """
    report = classification_report(y_true, y_pred, target_names=target_names, zero_division=0)
    print(" Classification Report:\n")
    print(report)

def plot_feature_importance(model, feature_names, top_n=None, title="Feature Importances", figsize=(10, 6), color="skyblue"):
    """
    Plots feature importances for tree-based models.

    Parameters:
        model: Trained model with `feature_importances_` attribute
        feature_names (list): List of feature names
        top_n (int): Number of top features to display (default: all)
        title (str): Title of the plot
        figsize (tuple): Size of the figure
        color (str): Bar color
    """
    importances = model.feature_importances_
    feature_df = pd.DataFrame({
        'Feature': feature_names,
        'Importance': importances
    }).sort_values(by='Importance', ascending=False)

    if top_n:
        feature_df = feature_df.head(top_n)

    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    sns.barplot(x='Importance', y='Feature', data=feature_df, color=color)
    plt.title(title, fontsize=14, pad=10)
    plt.xlabel("Importance Score", fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel("Feature", fontsize=12)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

from sklearn.tree import export_graphviz
import graphviz

def render_tree_graphviz(model, feature_names, class_names=None):
    """
    Renders a decision tree using Graphviz directly inside a Jupyter Notebook.

    Parameters:
        model: Trained DecisionTreeClassifier or DecisionTreeRegressor
        feature_names (list): Names of the input features
        class_names (list): Optional list of class names for classification
    """
    dot_data = export_graphviz(
        model,
        out_file=None,
        feature_names=feature_names,
        class_names=class_names,
        filled=True,
        rounded=True,
        special_characters=True
    )
    return graphviz.Source(dot_data)

Key Observations For Baseline Model¶

  • For the basis of model evaluation, we'll be using Recall as the primary metric of evaluation
  • Recall essentially will help us identify how many of the potential liability customers who would possibly accept a loan we can reach out to.
  • Due to higher value/emphasis on increase customer base & revenue, we need to ensure we don't miss out on probable customers
  • The baseline model has a recall score of ~92% on the cross validation training sets while having a 88% recall on the unseen test set (170 of the 193) when predicting personal loan accepting customers.
  • The model is showing good generalisation capabilities.
  • However, we can try pruning techniques to try and optimise the decision tree, increase generalisation and performance
  • Based on the model's feature importance scores, Income & Education are the 2 most important factors for identfying personal loan customers. Other features that played important roles in prediction of loan accepting customers - Family Members, CC Avg & Age

FINAL VERDICT - We should propose using the pre-puned Decision Tree solution to help the bank identify customers who could accept personal loans

Actionable Insights & Recommendation For AllLife Bank¶

1) Target High-Income Customers: Customers with higher annual income are significantly more likely to accept personal loans. AllLife Bank can prioritize marketing efforts toward high-income segments with tailored messaging that emphasizes premium benefits and flexible repayment options.

2) Engage Customers with High Credit Card Spending: Credit card spending is a strong indicator of loan acceptance. AllLife Bank should identify high-spending credit card users and send them personalized loan offers aligned with their spending habits, such as travel, luxury, or lifestyle purchases.

3) Focus on Highly Educated Customers: Customers with graduate or professional degrees show higher conversion rates. AllLife Bank can craft campaigns that position personal loans as enablers for career growth, skill upgrades, or professional investments especially relevant to educated audiences.

4) Leverage Larger Family Size: Larger families are more inclined to take loans, likely due to broader financial needs. The Bank should highlight how personal loans can support family expenses like education, healthcare, or housing (they should make the message family-centric)

5) Cross-Sell to Existing Account Holders: Customers with existing deposit or securities accounts are more likely to take personal loans. AllLife Bank can consider cross-selling campaigns to offer bundled products, convenience, and loyalty benefits to customers already banking with them.
